<p style="font-size: large">
    For my project and critical issue, the specific species that comes into play is the humble Dragonfly. 
    Given the scientific name: <b><i>Sympetrum Flaveolum</i></b>, 
    the Dragonfly is an insect belonging to the order Odonata, and infraorder Anisoptera. 
    Dragonflies carry the characteristics of having large multi-faceted eyes, two pairs of wings, and an elongated body. 
    Dragonflies are very predatory beings and will usually hunt in aquatic areas. They feed on freshwater invertebrates, as well as tadpoles and even small fish.
</p>

<br /><br />

<img src="~/images/dragonflymating.jpg" alt="Failed to load image / dragonflymating.jpg" width="800" height="500" />

<br /><br />

<p style="font-size: large">
    Dragonfly mating is complex and involves indirect sperm transfer, sperm storage, delayed fertilization, and even sperm competition. 
    Males will usually defend territories near water, which provide a suitable habitat for their larvae to develop, and for females to lay eggs. 
    As for their life cycle, Dragonflies are hemimetabolous insects; they do not have a pupal stage and undergo an incomplete metamorphosis with a series of nymphal stages from which the adult emerges.
</p>

<br /><br />

<img src="~/images/stmd.jpg" alt="Failed to load image / stmd.jpg" width="800" height="500" />

